M|When|Use |
M|When|it|Making a consequential decision that is hard to reverse
M|When|it|Evaluating a plan, ADR, or ds before commitment
M|When|it|You want structured adversarial feedback, not just a second opinion
M|When|Use |
M|When|it|You need st challenge on direction (whether, not how)
M|When|it|The question is abt project scope or priorities, not tc reasoning
M|Anti|tx|\| Avoid \| Why \| Instead \|
M|Anti|tx|\|-------\|-----\|---------\|
M|Anti|tx|\| Running critique after commitment \| Too late to change course \| Critique before finalizing decisions \|
M|Anti|tx|\| Accepting STAND verdict w/o reading al \| Misses nuanced findings \| rv all UNCERTAIN and FAILED items \|
M|Anti|tx|\| Skipping the inversion step \| Misses fl modes that forward reasoning overlooks \| Always run Steps 5-6 \|
M|Anti|tx|\| Using for trivial decisions \| Wastes time on lo-stakes choices \| Reserve for consequential, hard-to-reverse decisions \|
M|Veri|Afte|
M|Veri|- [ |VERIFIED, FAILED, or UNCERTAIN
M|Veri|it|[ ] Contrarian perspective generated (Step 5)
M|Veri|- [ |STAND, REVISE, ESCALATE
M|Veri|it|[ ] Inversion al covers at least 3 fl modes
M|Refe|it|[Chesterton's Fence](references/mental-md-chestertons-fence.md) - Understand why something exists before removing or changing it
M|Refe|it|[Gall's Law](references/mental-md-galls-law.md) - Complex working systems evolved from simple working systems
M|Refe|it|[Boy Scout Rule](references/qual-boy-scout-rule.md) - Scope boundaries for incremental improvement decisions
M|Refe|it|[Survivorship Bias](references/ct-thinking-survivorship-bias.md) - Avoid drawing conclusions from winners while ignoring failures
M|Refe|it|[Systems Thinking](references/st-thinking-systems-thinking.md) - Trace second-order effects and feedback loops in decisions
M|Acad|This|
M|Acad|tx|1. **Chain-of-Verification** (Dhuliawala et al., 2023) - Factored verification prevents confirmation bias
M|Acad|tx|2. **Self-Consistency** (Wang et al., 2023) - Multiple reasoning paths reveal disagreement
M|Acad|tx|3. **Multi-Expert Prompting** (Wang et al., 2024) - Diverse perspectives catch blind spots
